messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full HTTP request path:
  /api/products/{id}

- All HTTP methods acceptable:
  No

- HEAD:
  No
  Explanation: The code does not register an explicit handler for HEAD on this route. (Per instructions, do not assume framework behavior beyond what's in the code.)

- POST:
  No
  Explanation: POST handlers exist for /api/products (createProduct) and /api/products/:id/reviews (createProductReview), but there is no POST registered for /api/products/:id.

- OPTIONS:
  No
  Explanation: No explicit OPTIONS handler is defined for this path in the provided code.

- TRACE:
  No
  Explanation: No explicit TRACE handler is defined.

- GET:
  Yes
  Explanation: routes/productRoutes.js registers router.get('/:id', checkObjectId, getProductById). The router is mounted at /api/products in server.js, giving /api/products/:id (presented above as /api/products/{id}).

- PUT:
  Yes
  Explanation: routes/productRoutes.js registers router.put('/:id', protect, admin, checkObjectId, updateProduct). That maps to PUT /api/products/:id. updateProduct is the controller implemented in controllers/productController.js.

- DELETE:
  Yes
  Explanation: routes/productRoutes.js registers router.delete('/:id', protect, admin, checkObjectId, deleteProduct), mapping to DELETE /api/products/:id.

- PATCH:
  No
  Explanation: No PATCH handler is defined for /api/products/:id.

Additional notes:
- The router from routes/productRoutes.js is mounted at app.use('/api/products', productRoutes) in server.js, which is how the full path is formed.
- The path parameter name is id (hence {id} in the path).
- Some of the allowed methods require middleware (protect and admin for PUT and DELETE), as shown in the route declarations.
